From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Andrei Radulescu <andi.radulescu@gmail.com>
Date: Sat, 29 Mar 2026 08:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] ufs: core: wait for pending commands before shutdown

During system poweroff, ufshcd_wl_shutdown() calls __ufshcd_wl_suspend()
without first waiting for outstanding UFS commands to complete. If any
commands are in flight (e.g. from filesystem sync or background ops),
the doorbell bits remain set and the shutdown path hangs with repeated
"timedout waiting for doorbell to clear" errors, eventually causing an
RCU stall.

The Qualcomm downstream kernel (4.19) handles this correctly: it
suspends clock scaling, blocks SCSI requests, waits for the doorbell
to clear, and flushes the error handler before suspending.

Add the same sequence to ufshcd_wl_shutdown() using functions already
available in mainline: ufshcd_clk_scaling_suspend(), scsi_block_requests(),
ufshcd_wait_for_pending_cmds(), and flush_work().

---
 drivers/ufs/core/ufshcd.c | 17 +++++++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 17 insertions(+)

diff --git a/drivers/ufs/core/ufshcd.c b/drivers/ufs/core/ufshcd.c
index d6a060a72461..be3b8d3ff70f 100644
--- a/drivers/ufs/core/ufshcd.c
+++ b/drivers/ufs/core/ufshcd.c
@@ -10398,6 +10398,23 @@ static void ufshcd_wl_shutdown(struct device *dev)
 	/* Turn on everything while shutting down */
 	ufshcd_rpm_get_sync(hba);
 	scsi_device_quiesce(sdev);
+
+	/* Suspend clock scaling to prevent devfreq racing with shutdown */
+	ufshcd_clk_scaling_suspend(hba, true);
+
+	/* Block new requests and wait for in-flight commands to drain */
+	scsi_block_requests(hba->host);
+	if (ufshcd_wait_for_pending_cmds(hba, 5 * USEC_PER_SEC))
+		dev_err(hba->dev,
+			"%s: pending commands did not complete\n", __func__);
+
+	/*
+	 * The error handler may have been triggered by timed-out commands.
+	 * Flush it before proceeding with suspend.
+	 */
+	flush_work(&hba->eh_work);
+	scsi_unblock_requests(hba->host);
+
 	shost_for_each_device(sdev, hba->host) {
 		if (sdev == hba->ufs_device_wlun)
 			continue;
-- 
